article.description: Allen Iverson scored 32 points as the 76ers rolled to their fourth straight victory, a 103-83 triumph over the Heat, who have lost six straight home games.
article.headline: Sixers singe Heat with 56 percent shooting
article.linkText: Sixers squelch Heat, keep pace with first-place Nets
article.story:
MIAMI (AP) -- Allen Iverson and the Philadelphia 76ers just keep rolling along. Iverson scored 32 points and the 76ers kept pace with the Nets in the Atlantic Division by coasting to a 103-83 victory over the Miami Heat on Tuesday night. The Sixers, 15-2 since the All-Star break, stayed a half-game behind New Jersey for first place in the Atlantic Division, improving to 40-26. Philadelphia shot 56 percent and never led by fewer than eight points in the second half. "We've just been playing good team basketball, and our chemistry is a lot better when we understand what we want to do and how we want to score night in and night out,'' Iverson said. "It doesn't really matter if we play a good team or a bad team. We just want to rack up as many wins as we can.'' Iverson, averaging 32.1 points in his last eight games, went 13-of-25 from the field to go along with six assists. It was his 29th game this season with 30 or more points. Keith Van Horn scored 17 points and Kenny Thomas added 16 for the Sixers, who completed a four-game season sweep of the Heat. "It was a good win for us,'' Sixers coach Larry Brown said. "Any time you win on the road, you have to be happy.'' Miami continued its descent toward the draft lottery. The Heat have lost six of seven overall and five straight at home. Rookie Caron Butler scored a season-high 26 points and was the Heat's only starter to reach double figures in scoring. "Obviously, we were outclassed,'' Heat coach Pat Riley said. "They shot the ball extremely well. We were outrebounded, and we didn't play with a lot of energy and effort. We weren't in it tonight, and that's the disappointing part of it. We have to bring a major, major competitive effort, and they took that right away from us.'' The Sixers never trailed, grabbing a 28-18 lead at the end of the first quarter and opening a 45-26 lead midway through the second period. Philadelphia shot 60 percent in the first half and led 54-37. The Heat chipped away, pulling within 72-60 after three periods and closing to 74-66 on Butler's bucket. However, Iverson and Van Horn each followed with 3-pointers to extend the Sixers' lead to 80-66 with 9:33 remaining. Butler was the only bright spot for the Heat, who have tested Riley's patience this season as the losses have mounted. For Butler, it was the third time in his last five games that he has scored at least 20 points -- a stat Riley was well aware of. "He's playing well. We're going to him a lot,'' Riley said. "He wants to be good, and that's one of his great attributes. He's going to be great. He's a rookie right now on a team that's struggling, but he's playing well, and I'm proud of that.'' Few teams are playing as well as the Sixers, who have made up a lot of ground since the All-Star break. "They've always been tough because of Iverson, (Aaron) McKie and (Eric) Snow,'' Heat forward Malik Allen said. "But now you throw in Van Horn and Kenny Thomas, and they're even better. When they play the way they did tonight, they're really tough.''

Game notes
Sixers center Derrick Coleman suffered a bruised left hand in the third quarter and didn't return. X-rays revealed nothing serious, and Coleman was optimistic that he'll be ready against the Pistons on Thursday. ... The Sixers have won 10 of the last 15 games against the Heat, including four straight in Miami. ... Brown now has 1,100 wins when combining his NBA and ABA records. ...Brian Grant had seven defensive rebounds in the first quarter for the Heat, a season-high for any quarter by a Heat player. ... Riley juggled his lineup, starting Anthony Carter and Eddie House in the backcourt over Travis Best and Rasual Butler. The duo was a combined 4-of-21 from the field. ... The loss gave Riley a first-ever four-game sweep against a division opponent. ... With the Heat trailing 57-37, Anthony Carter was called for a flagrant foul against Iverson, who was taken down while driving to the basket.
